<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="diagnostic features">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Diagnostic features.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
It is distinct from individuals of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. vanensis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vanensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">P. vanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. by flatter elytral intervals and less coarsely punctate elytral striae. Measurements and ratios shown on Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="T1" captionText="Table 1. Morphometric data for species of the ' Platyderus weiratheri ' and ' Platyderus Eremoderus iranicus - Platyderus Eremoderus vanensis ' groups of Platyderus." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/ADBAD32C4643AAB3D1823CD894BA80BA" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" tableUuid="ADBAD32C4643AAB3D1823CD894BA80BA">1</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Habitat and bionomic notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
The specimen was collected by PM just before the pass Karabet Pass (eastern slope), on the road coming from Yukari-Narlica 
<normalizedToken originalValue="köyü">koeyue</normalizedToken>
village towards the pass. There is a large cirque on the left with many snowfields and streams descending from them; it was found in gravel between the rivulets, at an altitude of about 2800 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
Karabet Pass [= Karabet 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Geçidi">Gecidi</normalizedToken>
] (Turkey, Eastern Anatolia Region, Van Province).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71">The single female remains unidentified due to the lack of a male specimen. In addition, the characters of the elytral intervals and striae are not sufficiently diagnostic to propose a new name for this form.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
